value.value: This gene is involved in the transport of inorganic phosphate and glucose-6-phosphate across the endoplasmic reticulum membrane.

Disintegrin and metalloproteinase domain-containing protein 15 (863 aa, ~93 kDa) is encoded by the human ADAM15 gene. This protein is involved in cell-cell interactions, extracellular matrix protein metabolism and cell adhesion.

Human SLC37A4 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11q23.3 and is approximately 7 kb in length. This allele, which encodes glucose-6-phosphate exchanger SLC37A4 protein, plays a role in the localization of cytoplasmic glucose-6-phosphate in the lumen of the endoplasmic reticulum. Mutation of the gene is associated with glycogen storage disease types 1B, 1C and 1D.
An autosomal dominant form of spinocerebellar ataxia caused by mutation(s) in the TBP gene, encoding TATA-box-binding protein.

Glucose-6-phosphate exchanger SLC37A4 (429 aa, ~46 kDa) is encoded by the human SLC37A4 gene. This protein is involved in the export of inorganic phosphate out of and import of glucose-6-phosphate into the endoplasmic reticulum.
An autosomal recessive subtype of hereditary spastic paraplegia caused by mutation(s) in the AP4M1 gene, encoding AP-4 complex subunit mu-1.
A change in the nucleotide sequence of the SLC37A4 gene.

label.value: SLC37A4 Loss of Function Gene Mutation

value.value: A change in the nucleotide sequence of the SLC37A4 gene that either inhibits expression or results in the translation of an inactive glucose-6-phosphate exchanger SLC37A4 protein.
An autosomal recessive form of early infantile epileptic encephalopathy, caused by mutation(s) in the ARX gene, encoding homeobox protein ARX.
Presence of testes in an individual with a 46,XX karyotype associated with translocation of the SRY gene, encoding the transcription factor sex-determining region Y protein (SRY-positive).

label.value: Cardiac, Facial, and Digital Anomalies with Developmental Delay

value.value: An autosomal dominant condition caused by mutation(s) in the TRAF7 gene, encoding E3 ubiquitin-protein ligase TRAF7. It is characterized by developmental delay, cardiac, facial, and digital anomalies.
This gene plays a role in protein trafficking and both heterotypic and homotypic vesicle fusions.

Somatostatin receptor type 4 (388 aa, ~42 kDa) is encoded by the human SSTR4 gene. This protein plays a role in the inhibition of proliferation, stimulation of arachidonate release and activation of the mitogen-activated protein (MAP) kinase cascade.

Human VPS41 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 7p14.1 and is approximately 209 kb in length. This allele, which encodes vacuolar protein sorting-associated protein 41 homolog protein, is involved in cellular protein trafficking and vesicle membrane fusion.
Vacuolar protein sorting-associated protein 41 homolog (854 aa, ~96 kDa) is encoded by the human VPS41 gene. This protein plays a role in vesicle membrane fusion and protein trafficking.
This gene is involved in regulating the cardiovascular effects of angiotensin II.

Human AGTR1 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 3q24 and is approximately 45 kb in length. This allele, which encodes type-1 angiotensin II receptor protein, plays a role in angiotensin II-dependent signaling. Mutation of the gene is associated with essential hypertension and renal tubular dysgenesis.
Type-1 angiotensin II receptor (359 aa, ~41 kDa) is encoded by the human AGTR1 gene. This protein is involved in modulation of blood pressure and blood volume.
This gene plays a role in calcium-dependent phospholipid scrambling.

Human ANO6 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 12q12 and is approximately 266 kb in length. This allele, which encodes anoctamin-6 protein, is involved in phospholipid scrambling. A splice acceptor site mutation is associated with Scott syndrome.

Anoctamin-6 (910 aa, ~106 kDa) is encoded by the human ANO6 gene. This protein plays a role in calcium-dependent cell surface exposure of phosphatidylserine which triggers clotting in platelets and the deposition of hydroxyapatite by osteoblasts.
This gene is involved in the inhibition of viral membrane fusion.

Human IFITM2 wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 11p15.5 and is approximately 6 kb in length. This allele, which encodes interferon-induced transmembrane protein 2, plays a role in interferon-dependent antiviral responses, cell cycle arrest and caspase-dependent apoptosis.
G1/S-specific cyclin-D1 (295 aa, ~34 kDa) is encoded by the human CCND1 gene. This protein is involved in the regulation of the G1/S transition of the cell cycle.
Interferon-induced transmembrane protein 2 (132 aa, ~15 kDa) is encoded by the human IFITM2 gene. This protein is involved in cell cycle arrest, caspase-dependent apoptosis and antiviral responses.

A brief, multi-component behavioral sleep intervention designed to be used by primary care practices for the treatment of insomnia. The intervention involves two in-person sessions, each lasting 30 to 75 minutes, and two "booster" telephone sessions, each lasting less than 20 minutes, that focus on modifying sleep behaviors that influence homeostatic and circadian sleep regulation, including sleep restriction, stimulus control, and sleep hygiene.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the basal ganglia.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the cerebellar peduncle.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the corpus callosum.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the optic tract.
A benign or malignant neoplasm that affects the optic chiasm.
This gene plays a role in innate antiviral immunity.

An extremely rare, well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the esophagus. It is characterized by the presence of hyperkeratosis, acanthosis, dyskeratosis, keratin-filled cysts, koilocyte-like cells, intraepithelial neutrophils, and focal cytologic atypia.
A cyst that contains keratin.

An adenovirus nuclear membrane glycoprotein synthesized from the E3 transcription unit in large amounts late in infection.  It is required for efficient lysis of infected cells.  It is being investigated for use in targeting tumors for death by a suicide mechanism.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of neutrophils within neoplastic or non-neoplastic epithelium.
A morphologic finding indicating the presence of localized cytologic atypia in a tissue sample.

Human MAVS wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 20p13 and is approximately 30 kb in length. This allele, which encodes mitochondrial antiviral-signaling protein, is involved in the induction of antiviral immune responses.
Mitochondrial antiviral-signaling protein (540 aa, ~57 kDa) is encoded by the human MAVS gene. This protein plays a role in signaling that promotes the expression of antiviral cytokines.

A variant of well-differentiated squamous cell carcinoma arising from the oral cavity. It is characterized by the presence of minimal cytological atypia, multiple keratin-filled crypts, and intraepithelial neutrophils.
This gene is involved in glutathione biosynthesis.
A brief, seven-item questionnaire that considers physical dependence, environmental factors, and individual difference characteristics in predicting a patient's relapse from smoking cessation.

label.value: Place of Work's Smoking Policy for Work Areas

value.value: A question about the smoking policy in work areas at an individual's place of work.

Human GSS wild-type allele is located in the vicinity of 20q11.22 and is approximately 28 kb in length. This allele, which encodes glutathione synthetase protein, plays a role in ATP-dependent synthesis of glutathione. Mutation of the gene is associated with glutathione synthetase deficiency with or without hemolytic anemia.

label.value: Have to Leave in Order to Smoke

value.value: A question about whether an individual needs to leave the house to be able to smoke.

A cancer vaccine adjuvant consisting of a combination of the active monophosphoryl lipid A component of lipopolysaccharide (LPS) isolated from the bacterium Salmonella minnesota combined with a residue of the cell wall of the bacterium Mycobacterium phlei.  Detox is a non-specific immunostimulant that may enhance the host immune response to certain cancer vaccines. (NCI04)
Histone acetyltransferase KAT2B (832 aa, ~93 kDa) is encoded by the human KAT2B gene. This protein is involved in both histone acetylation and transcriptional activation.

label.value: Around Smokers Much of the Time

value.value: A question about whether an individual is around smokers much of the time.
Glutathione synthetase (474 aa, ~52 kDa) is encoded by the human GSS gene. This protein is involved in the reversible synthesis of glutathione from L-cysteine and L-glutamate.

label.value: Craving Gets Intolerable When Unable to Smoke for a few Hours

value.value: A question about whether an individual's cravings get intolerable if they have not been able to smoke for a few hours.
